:prostatic_hypertrophy rdfs:subClassOf :prostate_disease .
text: prostatic hypertrophy is a type of prostate disease.
A prostatic cyst, which is a type of prostatic hypertrophy, is exactly synonymous with cyst of the prostate.
Prolapse of the lacrimal gland is a type of lacrimal apparatus disease and it occurs specifically in the lacrimal gland. It is also exactly synonymous with the dislocation of the lacrimal gland.

Esophagus sarcoma is a type of sarcoma and a type of esophageal cancer. It falls under the category of diseases that originate from embryonic cell metazoa and are located in the esophagus. The definition of esophagus sarcoma is an esophageal cancer that arises from transformed cells of mesenchymal origin and is located in the esophagus. Additionally, esophagus sarcoma is also known by its related synonym, esophageal sarcoma.

Hypersecretion glaucoma is a type of glaucoma characterized by high aqueous fluid production and inflow relative to aqueous fluid outflow, leading to inappropriately elevated intraocular pressure. This condition may result in optic nerve damage and visual field loss. The symptoms of hypersecretion glaucoma include pain, loss of vision, bloodshot eyes, and headaches. Additionally, it has features such as ocular hypertension. Specifically, hypersecretion glaucoma is associated with progressive peripheral vision loss, decreased vision, and in acute cases, pain, redness, and headache, which are caused by the high aqueous fluid inflow relative to outflow.

Aqueous misdirection is a type of glaucoma characterized by a shallowing of the central and peripheral anterior chamber due to posterior pressure, resulting in inappropriately elevated intraocular pressure. This condition leads to optic nerve damage and visual field loss, with symptoms including some pain, loss of vision, bloodshot eyes, and headache. Additionally, aqueous misdirection is associated with features like ocular hypertension. The disease is caused by an abnormal relationship between the ciliary body, lens, and anterior vitreous, which diverts aqueous flow into the posterior segment, thereby increasing posterior pressure and further closing the angle. Aqueous misdirection can occur in association with glaucoma surgery, trauma, endophthalmitis, and retinopathy of prematurity. It also has symptoms such as progressive peripheral vision loss, decreased vision, and, in acute cases, pain, redness, and headache.

Sarcoma is the same as something that is the intersection of something that is cancer and something that at least derives from some embryonic cell metazoa. It is a type of cell type cancer. Sarcoma is defined as a cell type cancer that has its material basis in abnormally proliferating cells derived from embryonic mesoderm. Additionally, sarcoma has exact synonyms, including connective and soft tissue neoplasm, as well as tumor of soft tissue and skeleton.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:cholecystolithiasis rdfs:subClassOf :gallbladder_disease .
text: cholecystolithiasis is a type of gallbladder disease.

Miliaria rubra is a type of miliaria, characterized by erythematous papules that result in the leakage of sweat into the deeper, subcorneal layers of the epidermis, provoking a local inflammatory reaction. It is also exactly known as prickly heat.

Hypohidrosis is a type of sweat gland disease and is also known as Oligohidrosis, with an exact match in the MESH database under the identifier D007007. It is characterized by a reduced ability to sweat and has symptoms such as hyperthermia and dry skin in the affected areas. The condition arises due to trauma to the sweat glands. Additionally, hypohidrosis is identified as a condition that, at the very least, results in symptoms like hyperthermia.

Anhidrosis is a type of hypohidrosis and falls under the category of diseases that characteristically feature anhidrosis as well as those that exhibit symptoms such as hyperthermia. It is defined as a hypohidrosis that is characterized by the inability to sweat, leading to symptoms like hyperthermia and dry skin. Moreover, anhidrosis is also precisely known as Adiaphoresis and the absence of sweating.

Pertussis, also known as whooping cough, WC - Whooping cough, and bordetella infection, is a commensal bacterial infectious disease. It is characterized by inflammation located in the respiratory tract and results from either Bordetella pertussis or Bordetella parapertussis. These bacteria produce toxins that paralyze the cilia of the respiratory epithelial cells, leading to the infection's hallmark: a prolonged, high-pitched, deeply indrawn breath known as a "whoop". Pertussis is defined by its basis in material that encompasses both Bordetella parapertussis and Bordetella pertussis.

Neonatal respiratory failure is a type of respiratory failure and it is defined as a respiratory failure characterized by inadequate gas exchange by the respiratory system in neonates. It is also exactly synonymous with respiratory failure of the newborn.

Respiratory failure is a type of lung disease characterized by inadequate gas exchange by the respiratory system. It is also known by exact synonyms including acute and chronic respiratory failure, acute respiratory failure, acute-on-chronic respiratory failure, chronic respiratory failure, and respiratory insufficiency/failure.
Band keratopathy, which has the exact synonym "Band-shaped keratopathy," is a type of corneal degeneration.

Common wart is a type of viral infectious disease and is a type of condition that has a material basis in some human papillomavirus types. It is defined as a viral infectious disease that results in an infection located in the skin, which has a material basis in human papillomavirus (types 2 and 4). This infection is characterized by a raised wart with a roughened surface, most commonly found on the hands, but can grow anywhere on the body.

Human papillomavirus infectious disease (HPV) is a type of viral infectious disease and also a type of disease that is at least transmitted by contact transmission. It is defined as a viral infectious disease that has a material basis in human papillomaviruses, which establish productive infections only in the stratified epithelium of the skin or mucous membranes. These viruses are responsible for causing warts and sometimes tumors and are transmitted by sexual contact.

Anogenital venereal wart is a type of viral infectious disease that has a material basis in some alphapapillomavirus 10 and is transmitted by some contact transmission. This disease primarily affects regions including the uterine cervix, oral cavity, throat, penis, uterus, vagina, anus, and scrotum. It is defined as a viral infectious disease resulting in infection located in the skin of the vagina, cervix, uterus, anus, penis, scrotum, mouth, or throat. This infection is caused by human papillomaviruses (types 6 and 11), which are transmitted through direct contact with the skin during oral, genital, or anal sex with an infected partner and is characterized by the symptom of anogenital warts.

Additionally, the disease is known by several exact synonyms, including Anogenital Human Papilloma Virus Infectious Disease, Anogenital warts, Genital warts, Genital wart virus infectious disease, and Venereal wart. It also has a related synonym, Condyloma acuminatum.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:enophthalmos rdfs:subClassOf :orbital_disease .
text: enophthalmos is a type of orbital disease.
Total internal ophthalmoplegia is a type of disease that affects eye accommodation and the pupil. It is characterized by its involvement with the pupil.

Non-suppurative otitis media is a type of otitis media defined as an otitis media that involves the transudation of fluid in the middle ear without pus formation. It is also exactly synonymous with Nonsuppurative otitis media.

Serous glue ear is a type of non-suppurative otitis media, defined as a non-suppurative otitis media characterized by an effusion with very thick and glue-like middle ear fluid, which may cause conductive hearing impairment.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:acute_conjunctivitis rdfs:subClassOf :conjunctivitis .
text: acute conjunctivitis is a type of conjunctivitis.

Allescheriosis is a type of primary systemic mycosis and is also known by its exact synonym, Petriellidosis. It is characterized by being a condition that has a material basis in Pseudallescheria boydii, previously referred to as some Scedosporium boydii. This condition results in systemic fungal infections, leading to the formation of abscesses, thus highlighting abscess as one of its symptoms.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:pulp_degeneration rdfs:subClassOf :dental_pulp_disease .
text: pulp degeneration is a type of dental pulp disease.

Pseudomembranous conjunctivitis is a type of acute conjunctivitis defined by the formation of a fibrin-rich exudate on the surface of the conjunctiva. The causes of pseudomembranes in this condition can be infectious, including Corynebacterium diphtheriae, streptococci, pneumococci, herpes simplex virus, adenovirus, Chlamydia, and gonococci. Additionally, non-infectious causes are chemical (alkali) irritants, erythema multiforme, and ocular pemphigoid.

Syndactyly is a type of synostosis and also falls under the category of conditions that invariably exhibit some form of abnormal digit morphology. It is defined as a synostosis resulting in the fusion of two or more digits. Syndactyly is precisely synonymous with chromosome 2q35 duplication syndrome, symphalangism, symphalangy, and webbing of digits. Additionally, it has an exact match in the MESH database with the identifier D013576.
Acute laryngopharyngitis is a type of upper respiratory tract disease characterized by inflammation of both the larynx and pharynx.

Serous conjunctivitis, except viral, is a type of acute conjunctivitis and also falls under the category of conditions that at least have the symptom of some inflammation. It is defined as a viral acute conjunctivitis characterized by conjunctival inflammation and serous discharge. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with serous conjunctivitis, except viral.

Di George syndrome is a type of syndrome, which is an autosomal dominant disease and also a chromosomal deletion syndrome. It is characterized by an intersection of characteristics that include at least having a material basis in some deletion and in some chromosome, specifically having a basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and in some gene-related disease. Di George syndrome is defined as a syndrome that has its material basis in a large deletion of the chromosome 22q11.2 region, which includes the DGS gene necessary for the development of the thymus and related glands, leading to a lack of T-cell production. Furthermore, Di George syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including 22q11.2 deletion syndrome, DiGeorge sequence, DiGeorge's syndrome, and Pharyngeal pouch syndrome.

Hypoparathyroidism is a type of parathyroid gland disease. It is defined as a parathyroid gland disease characterized by decreased function of the parathyroid glands with underproduction of parathyroid hormone (PTH), leading to abnormally low ionized calcium levels in the blood. Hypoparathyroidism has an exact match with MESH:D007011.

Esophageal varix is defined as an intersection of vein disease and diseases that, at the very least, are located in the esophagus, making it a specific type of both esophageal and vein disease. It is exactly synonymous with various terms including Bleeding esophageal varices, Bleeding oesophageal varices, esophageal varices, esophageal varices in disease classified elsewhere, with bleeding, esophageal varices with bleeding, esophageal varices with bleeding in disease EC, esophageal varices without bleeding, and esophageal varices without mention of bleeding.

T cell deficiency is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease that is characterized by decreased numbers of circulating or functioning T cells. It is also exactly synonymous with T cell immunodeficiency, T lymphocyte deficiency, and T lymphocyte immunodeficiency.

Parathyroid gland disease, which is exactly synonymous with the disease of parathyroid glands, is identified as a type of endocrine system disease. It is defined as an endocrine system disease that is located in the parathyroid gland. Furthermore, parathyroid gland disease is equivalent to an intersection involving a disease that has a location in the parathyroid gland and encompasses at least one disease associated with the parathyroid gland.

Primary hyperparathyroidism is a type of hyperparathyroidism that is characterized by the overproduction of parathyroid hormone and elevated levels of calcium in the blood. It is also exactly synonymous with familial primary hyperparathyroidism.
Angelucci's syndrome, which is a type of allergic conjunctivitis, is also exactly known as Angelucci syndrome and acute atopic conjunctivitis.

Allergic conjunctivitis is a type of allergic disease, chronic conjunctivitis, and a condition that involves at least some allergic reaction as symptoms. It is defined as a chronic conjunctivitis characterized by inflammation of the conjunctiva, involving red, itchy, and watery eyes resulting from exposure to an allergen or irritant.
Opioid abuse is a type of substance abuse characterized by a pattern where individuals repeatedly use opioid drugs despite facing negative consequences.

Buphthalmos, also known as primary congenital glaucoma 3A or simple buphthalmos, is a specific type of hydrophthalmos. It is characterized by an early onset of glaucoma in one or both eyes, leading to symptoms such as early vision loss, photophobia, blepharospasm, tearing, increased corneal diameter, increased corneal thickness, and an enlarged globe. This condition is caused by severe congenital defects of the trabecular meshwork and anterior chamber angle, which obstruct aqueous outflow and result in raised intraocular pressure. Consequently, this leads to optic nerve atrophy and early vision loss. Additionally, buphthalmos is associated with diseases that feature symptoms like photophobia, blepharospasm, and ocular hypertension.

Hydrophthalmos, a type of primary congenital glaucoma, is characterized by early onset glaucoma in one or both eyes with elevated intraocular pressure and increased corneal diameter. This condition is also a type of something that at least disease has feature some ocular hypertension. It has symptoms including early vision loss, increased corneal diameter, and increased corneal thickness. The cause of Hydrophthalmos is congenital defects of the trabecular meshwork and anterior chamber angle that block aqueous outflow, leading to optic nerve atrophy and early vision loss due to raised intraocular pressure.

Acute contagious conjunctivitis is a type of acute conjunctivitis defined as a bacterial acute conjunctivitis characterized by highly contagious conjunctival hyperemia and mucopurulent discharge, with its material basis in Hemophilius Aegypticus. It is also exactly synonymous with Contagious opthalmia, Pink eye, and Pinkeye.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:chronic_tympanitis rdfs:subClassOf :tympanic_membrane_disease .
text: chronic tympanitis is a type of tympanic membrane disease.

Conjunctival folliculosis is a type of acute conjunctivitis, defined as an acute conjunctivitis characterized by conjunctival folliculosis and follicular hypertrophy of the palpebral conjunctivae. It is also exactly synonymous with acute follicular conjunctivitis.

Small intestine diverticulitis is the same as something that is an intersection of diverticulitis and a disease that has its location in the small intestine. It is a type of diverticulitis. Additionally, small intestine diverticulitis has an exact synonym: Diverticulosis of the small intestine with hemorrhage.

Acute hemorrhagic conjunctivitis is a type of conjunctival disease and a viral infectious disease that is characterized by inflammation located in the conjunctiva. This condition is known to have a material basis in Human coxsackievirus A24 or Human enterovirus 70, which are transmitted by contact transmission and vehicle-borne fomite transmission. The symptoms associated with acute hemorrhagic conjunctivitis include photophobia, bloodshot eyes, and conjunctival congestion. Furthermore, the disease predominantly affects the conjunctiva. Acute hemorrhagic conjunctivitis is also defined as a viral infectious disease that results in inflammation located in the conjunctiva, caused by Human coxsackievirus A24 or Human enterovirus 70, transmitted by contaminated fomites or contact with contaminated hands. The infection manifests symptoms such as vascular dilation, eyelid edema, photophobia, redness of the eyes, watering of the eye, conjunctival congestion, and superficial punctate epithelial keratitis.

Additionally, acute hemorrhagic conjunctivitis is known by other names including Apollo disease and Epidemic hemorrhagic conjunctivitis, and it is relatedly referred to as viral conjunctivitis.
Spondyloarthropathy is a type of arthropathy, which is exactly synonymous with both spondarthropathy and spondylarthrosis.
Acute orbital inflammation is a type of orbital disease and is characterized by having symptoms of inflammation. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with acute inflammation of the orbit.

Orbital periostitis is a type of acute orbital inflammation and is characterized by inflammation of the periosteum of the orbit. It is defined as an acute orbital inflammation that manifests at least some symptoms of inflammation.

Orbital osteomyelitis is a type of acute orbital inflammation, which is defined as an acute orbital inflammation characterized by inflammation of the medullary cavity of the orbital bone that eventually spreads to the periosteum.

Orbital tenonitis is a type of acute orbital inflammation characterized by inflammation of the capsule of Tenon, and it is also identified by at least having some inflammation as a symptom. Furthermore, orbital tenonitis is exactly synonymous with Tenonitis.

Orbital cellulitis is defined as an acute orbital inflammation characterized by a painful orbital mass, and it exhibits symptoms such as eyelid edema, erythema, chemiosis, proptosis, blurred vision, headache, fever, and double vision. This condition is a type of acute orbital inflammation and is known to have symptoms including inflammation, double vision, ptosis, headache, and fever.

Adhesive otitis media is a type of auditory system disease, which is defined as an auditory system disease characterized by a thin retracted eardrum that becomes sucked into the middle-ear space and adheres to the ossicles and other bones of the middle ear. It is exactly synonymous with chronic adhesive otitis media.

Appendix cancer, also known as cancer of the appendix, malignant neoplasm of appendix vermiformis, malignant tumor of appendix, and malignant tumor of the appendix, is a type of intestinal cancer and a form of appendix disease. It is defined as an intestinal cancer located in the appendix, equating to a condition that intersects with being a form of cancer and a disease with a location in the vermiform appendix.
Appendiceal neoplasm, which is a type of intestinal benign neoplasm, has exact synonyms including appendix neoplasm and neoplasm of appendix.

Appendix lymphoma is a type of lymphoma and also a type of appendix cancer. It is characterized by having a material basis in some lymphocyte. Additionally, appendix lymphoma is exactly synonymous with Appendiceal Lymphoma.
Plethora of newborn, which is a type of polycythemia, is exactly synonymous with Neonatal polycythemia.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:anemia_of_prematurity rdfs:subClassOf :neonatal_anemia .
text: anemia of prematurity is a type of neonatal anemia.
Neonatal anemia is a type of anemia, which is exactly synonymous with anaemia neonatal, anemia neonatal, and neonatal anaemia.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:transient_neonatal_neutropenia rdfs:subClassOf :neutropenia .
text: transient neonatal neutropenia is a type of neutropenia.
DIC in newborns is a type of disseminated intravascular coagulation, and it is exactly synonymized as Disseminated intravascular coagulation in newborns.
Disseminated intravascular coagulation is a type of thrombophilia, and it has exact synonyms such as DIC, Defibrination syndrome, and Diffuse or disseminated intravascular coagulation.

Vitamin K deficiency bleeding is a nutritional deficiency disease characterized by easy bleeding due to an inability to form blood clots, which is caused by a deficiency of vitamin K. This condition most commonly occurs in newborns and has a material basis in factors such as liver prematurity, lack of vitamin K in a breastmilk diet, a largely sterile gut, malabsorption, diarrhea, chronic illness, menorrhagia, chronic kidney disease, and some medications. It exhibits symptoms such as bleeding and diarrhea. Vitamin K deficiency bleeding is also precisely known as deficiency of vitamin K, vitamin K deficiency, and vitamin K deficiency hemorrhagic disease.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:microcytic_anemia rdfs:subClassOf :anemia .
text: microcytic anemia is a type of anemia.

Brill Zinsser disease is a type of epidemic typhus, defined as an epidemic typhus that is a mild form of the disease, which recurs in someone after a long period of latency due to immunosuppression, malnutrition, or other illnesses. It has exact synonyms including Brill Zinsser disease, Brill's disease, and Recrudescent typhus. In addition, it has related synonyms such as Latent typhus and Sporadic typhus.

fragment:
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:typhus rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :has_material_basis_in ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :rickettsia ],
        [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :transmitted_by ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :insect_borne_transmission ],
        :primary_bacterial_infectious_disease ;
    :has_definition "A primary bacterial infectious disease that refers to a group of diseases, located in endothelial cells of the small venous, arterial, and capillary vessels, has_material_basis_in Rickettsia bacteria, which are transmitted by lice, transmitted by fleas, and transmitted by mites." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "Endemic Typhus fever"@en,
        "Exanthematic Typhus fever"@en,
        "Flea typhus"@en,
        "Louse-borne [epidemic] typhus"@en,
        "Moscow typhus"@en,
        "Murine [endemic] typhus"@en,
        "Typhus fever"@en,
        "endemic flea-borne typhus"@en,
        "epidemic louse-borne typhus"@en ;
    :has_related_synonym "Classical typhus"@en,
        "Epidemic (louse-borne) typhus"@en,
        "Epidemic louse-borne typhus fever due to Rickettsia prowazekii"@en,
        "European typhus"@en,
        "Exanthematous typhus"@en,
        "Famine fever"@en,
        "Flea-borne rickettsiosis"@en,
        "Flea-borne typhus"@en,
        "Hospital fever"@en,
        "Jail fever"@en,
        "Louse-borne rickettsiosis"@en,
        "Louse-borne typhus"@en,
        "Mexican typhus"@en,
        "Murine typhus"@en,
        "Petechial fever"@en,
        "Prison fever"@en,
        "Rat flea typhus"@en,
        "Ship fever"@en,
        "Shop typhus"@en,
        "Typhus exanthematique"@en,
        "Urban typhus"@en .
text: Typhus is a primary bacterial infectious disease that is categorized as having a material basis in Rickettsia bacteria and is transmitted through insect-borne transmission mechanisms. This infectious disease is specifically located in the endothelial cells of small venous, arterial, and capillary vessels. It is known to be transmitted by lice, fleas, and mites. Typhus is recognized by several exact synonyms, including Endemic Typhus fever, Exanthematic Typhus fever, Flea typhus, Louse-borne [epidemic] typhus, Moscow typhus, Murine [endemic] typhus, Typhus fever, endemic flea-borne typhus, and epidemic louse-borne typhus. Moreover, it has related synonyms that reflect its varied manifestations and historical names, such as Classical typhus, Epidemic (louse-borne) typhus, Epidemic louse-borne typhus fever due to Rickettsia prowazekii, European typhus, Exanthematous typhus, Famine fever, Flea-borne rickettsiosis, Flea-borne typhus, Hospital fever, Jail fever, Louse-borne rickettsiosis, Louse-borne typhus, Mexican typhus, Murine typhus, Petechial fever, Prison fever, Rat flea typhus, Ship fever, Shop typhus, Typhus exanthematique, and Urban typhus.

Social phobia is a type of phobic disorder, defined as a phobic disorder that involves social anxiety occurring only in specific public or social situations, interactions with others, or being evaluated or scrutinized by other people.

Cat scratch disease is a type of bartonellosis, lymph node disease, and a condition that has a material basis in either Bartonella henselae or Bartonella clarridgeiae. It manifests with symptoms including backache, abdominal pain, headache, and chills, and is notably located in the lymph node. Defined as a bartonellosis that results in infection located in the lymph node and is transmitted by the scratch or bite of a kitten, or by contact with an animal's saliva on the eye or through broken skin, cat scratch disease features symptoms such as regional lymphadenopathy, headache, chills, backache, and abdominal pain. It is also known by several exact synonyms: Debre's Syndrome, Debre-Mollaret Syndrome, Foshay-Mollaret Cat Scratch Fever, benign lymphoreticulosis, and cat scratch fever.

Rabies is a type of viral infectious disease, also known exactly as Lyssa, characterized by being transmitted through contact, such as the bite of an infected animal or contact of mucous membranes with the saliva of an infected animal. It results in inflammation located either in the brain or the spinal cord and is caused by the Rabies virus. The disease manifests through a variety of symptoms including confusion, delirium, paralysis, anxiety, itching, dysphagia (difficulty swallowing), headache, fever, and agitation. Specifically, the infection presents with fever, headache, a prickling or itching sensation at the site of the bite, anxiety, confusion, agitation, delirium, difficulty swallowing, hydrophobia (fear of water), and paralysis.

Ornithosis, also known as psittacosis, is classified as a primary bacterial infectious disease. It results from a systemic infection that has its material basis in Chlamydia psittaci. This disease can be transmitted through inhaling aerosolized, dried droppings or by contact with infected birds, combining both contact and airborne transmission modes. The symptoms of ornithosis include fever, headache, rash, chills, and it also features pneumonia as a disease characteristic.

Chlamydia is a commensal bacterial infectious disease that is defined as a condition caused by Chlamydia trachomatis. It is a type of disease that not only has its material basis in Chlamydia trachomatis but is also transmitted through contact transmission. Additionally, Chlamydia is precisely known by several exact synonyms, including Chlamydia trachomatis infectious disease, Chlamydial Infection, and chlamydial disease.

Trachoma is a type of commensal bacterial infectious disease that is also an eye disease. It has a material basis in Chlamydia trachomatis, specifically the A, B, Ba, and C serovars. The disease is transmitted through contact with eye discharge from an infected person or through congenital methods. It is characterized by the infection causing the eyelid to turn inward, leading to the eyelashes scratching the cornea. Additionally, trachoma is known by the exact synonyms "active stage trachoma" and "trachoma dubium."

Hantavirus hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome (HFRS) is identified as a viral infectious disease that intersects with diseases located in the kidney. It is a type of kidney disease as well as a viral infectious disease. The disease primarily has a material basis in several orthohantaviruses, including Orthohantavirus dobravaense, Orthohantavirus hantanense, Orthohantavirus puumalaense, and Orthohantavirus seoulense. Furthermore, HFRS is characterized by a phenotype of renal insufficiency and presents symptoms such as proteinuria, headache, fever, renal failure, petechiae, and muscle pain. The disease's definition encompasses a hemorrhagic fever located in the kidney, caused by the aforementioned orthohantaviruses carried and transmitted by rodents, and features symptoms including headache, fever, muscle pains, facial flush, petechiae, proteinuria, and renal failure. Additionally, HFRS is known by several exact synonyms, including Hemorrhagic fever, Russian; Hemorrhagic nephrosonephritis; and Puumala virus nephropathy.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:keratomalacia rdfs:subClassOf :corneal_degeneration .
text: keratomalacia is a type of corneal degeneration.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:chronic_apical_periodontitis rdfs:subClassOf :periapical_periodontitis .
text: chronic apical periodontitis is a type of periapical periodontitis.
Plummer's disease, which is a type of hyperthyroidism, is also exactly synonymous with Plummer disease and toxic nodular goiter.
Solar retinopathy, which has the exact synonym Solar retinitis, is a type of chorioretinal scar.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:peripheral_scars_of_retina rdfs:subClassOf :chorioretinal_scar .
text: peripheral scars of retina is a type of chorioretinal scar.

Tick paralysis is a type of tick infestation and is characterized by an acute, ascending, flaccid motor paralysis. This condition occurs due to the introduction of a neurotoxin into humans during attachment and feeding by the females of several tick species, including Dermacentor andersoni, Dermacentor variabilis, Amblyomma americanum, Amblyomma maculatum, Ixodes scapularis, Ixodes pacificus, Ixodes holocyclus, Rhipicephalus sanguineus, and Otobius megnini. The symptoms of tick paralysis include local inflammation, edema, hemorrhage, flaccidity, and flaccid paralysis. Furthermore, tick paralysis has an exact match with MESH:D013985.

Ventilation pneumonitis is a type of extrinsic allergic alveolitis, which is defined as an extrinsic allergic alveolitis caused by inhalation of antigens from thermophilic actinomycetes species growing in air conditioners and humidifiers. Additionally, fungi like Aureobasidium sp and Candida albicans, which survive in the contaminated water in humidifiers and air conditioners, are also known to cause the disease. Ventilation pneumonitis is exactly synonymous with both "Air-conditioner and humidifier lung" and "Humidifier lung."

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:pituitary_apoplexy rdfs:subClassOf :pituitary_infarct .
text: pituitary apoplexy is a type of pituitary infarct.

Arteriovenous malformation is a type of hemangioma characterized by a configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins by bypassing the capillary system. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Arteriovenous hemangioma, Cirsoid aneurysm, Racemose Angioma, Racemose aneurysm, and Racemose hemangioma.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:retinal_microaneurysm rdfs:subClassOf :retinal_vascular_disease .
text: retinal microaneurysm is a type of retinal vascular disease.

Vertebral artery occlusion is identified as an intersection of conditions: those that involve occlusion of a precerebral artery and diseases that are located in the vertebral artery. It is classified as a type of artery disease and also as a type of occlusion of a precerebral artery. Additionally, vertebral artery occlusion is exactly synonymous with "Occlusion and stenosis of vertebral artery."
Pituitary infarct, which is a type of necrosis of the pituitary, has the exact synonym "Pituitary infarction."

Cercarial dermatitis, also known precisely as cutaneous schistosomiasis or sea bather's eruption, is a type of schistosomiasis and a skin disease that occurs in certain zones of the skin. It is defined as a schistosomiasis that manifests as a short-term, cutaneous inflammatory response associated with the penetration of the skin by cercariae of the bird schistosome, Austrobilharzia variglandis. The disease is characterized by symptoms such as skin reddening, itching in the water or immediately after emerging, and itchy, raised papules that occur within hours of infection.
Mobitz Type II atrioventricular block is a type of second degree atrioventricular block. It has exact synonyms including Mobitz (type) II atrioventricular block and Mobitz II atrioventricular block.

African histoplasmosis is a type of histoplasmosis that is also a type of condition transmitted by some form of airborne transmission. It is defined as a histoplasmosis that results in a systemic fungal infection, which is caused by Histoplasma capsulatum var duboisii. This infection is transmitted through airborne spores and leads to the formation of nodules, ulcers, and osteolytic bone lesions.
Histoplasmosis retinitis, which is a type of retinitis, is exactly synonymous with Histoplasmosis with retinitis.

Kyasanur Forest Disease is a viral infectious disease categorized as a hemorrhagic fever. It is fundamentally caused by the Kyasanur Forest Disease virus, which is transmitted through the bite of Haemaphysalis spinigera ticks. The disease is characterized by several symptoms including fever, headache, stiffness of the neck, severe muscle pain, cough, dehydration, and bleeding problems.
Schizophreniform disorder is a type of psychotic disorder that is defined as a psychotic disorder involving symptoms of schizophrenia over a time period of one month.

Ainhum is a type of connective tissue disease characterized by increasing fibrous constriction that ultimately leads to the spontaneous amputation of the toes, especially the little toes. It involves a painful constriction of the base of the fifth toe, frequently followed by bilateral spontaneous amputation (autoamputation) a few years later. Ainhum is also known exactly as Dactylolysis spontanea and has an exact match with the MESH identifier D000387.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:erysipelas rdfs:subClassOf :dermatitis .
text: erysipelas is a type of dermatitis.

Sarcoidosis is a type IV hypersensitivity reaction disease characterized by the growth of collections of inflammatory cells (granulomas) in multiple organs. It is also known by exact synonyms such as Boeck sarcoid and lymphogranulomatosis. Additionally, sarcoidosis has an exact match with MESH:D012507.

Rhinoscleroma is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that involves the inflammation of the mucosa lining the nasal cavity, pharynx, larynx, trachea, and bronchi. It is characterized by the formation of granulomas, dense induration of the tissues, and nodular deformity caused by Klebsiella rhinoscleromatis.

Lemierre's syndrome is a type of commensal bacterial infectious disease characterized by systemic sepsis, ulcerative or necrotic lesions, and multisystem abscesses caused by Fusobacterium necrophorum. It often first presents as severe tonsillitis or pharyngitis with high-grade fever and chills, accompanied by leukocytosis, cervical pain, and neck swelling. This syndrome has symptoms including leukocytosis, abscesses, and chills. Lemierre's syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms: Lemierre syndrome, human necrobacillosis, and postanginal sepsis. Additionally, it has a related synonym, acute sore throat.

Tetanus is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease, which is also known as clostridial tetanus or infection due to Clostridium tetani. It is characterized by prolonged contraction of skeletal muscle fibers. The disease has its material basis in Clostridium tetani, which produces tetanospasmin, a neurotoxin. This neurotoxin is carried to the brain and spinal cord, where it binds irreversibly to receptors, inhibiting neurotransmission. As a result, damaged upper motor neurons cannot control reflex responses to afferent sensory stimuli.

Pneumocystosis is an opportunistic mycosis and a type of lung disease that has its material basis in Pneumocystis jirovecii. It is characterized by symptoms such as fever, cough, and dyspnea. Specifically, this disease is located in the lungs, but it can also manifest in various other parts of the body including the eyes, ears, skin, thyroid, pituitary, palate, parathyroid, esophagus, pleura, heart, liver, spleen, small intestine, adrenals, kidneys, bone marrow, and lymph nodes. Pneumocystosis affects the interstitial and alveolar tissues and is associated with a nonproductive cough, shortness of breath, and fever. Moreover, it is also known by several exact synonyms: Pneumocystis carinii pneumonia, Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia, Pneumocystis pneumonia, Pneumocystosis pneumonia, and pulmonary pneumocystosis.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:gingival_recession rdfs:subClassOf :gingival_disease ;
    :has_exact_synonym "Gingival recession, localized"@en,
        "localized gingival recession"@en,
        "minimal gingival recession"@en,
        "moderate gingival recession"@en,
        "severe gingival recession"@en .
text: Gingival recession is a type of gingival disease and is synonymous with various terms, including Gingival recession, localized, localized gingival recession, minimal gingival recession, moderate gingival recession, and severe gingival recession.
Arcus senilis is a type of corneal degeneration, which is exactly synonymous with Arcus of cornea and corneal arcus.
Scleral disease is a type of eye disease characterized by affecting the sclera, which is the white fibrous outer layer of the eyeball.
Bladder diverticulum is a type of bladder disease and has exact synonyms such as Diverticulum - bladder and Diverticulum of bladder.
A stone in the bladder diverticulum, which is a type of bladder diverticulum, has the exact synonym calculus in the diverticulum of the bladder.
Bladder calculus is a type of bladder disease and lower urinary tract calculus, indicating it is something that has its location in the urinary bladder, associated with at least one disease.

Phlebotomus fever, also known exactly as Sandfly fever, Sandfly-borne arboviral fever, Sandfly-borne bunyavirus fever, Sandfly-borne phleboviral disease, and pappataci fever, is a type of viral infectious disease. It has a material basis in either the Sandfly fever Naples virus or the Sandfly fever Sicilian virus, which are transmitted by the Phlebotomus papatasi sandfly. This disease is characterized by symptoms such as fever, joint pain, flushing, tachycardia, severe frontal headaches, muscle ache, and joint aches.
Lens subluxation is a type of lens disease and has the exact synonym "Subluxation of lens." Furthermore, it has an exact match with MESH:D007906.

Congenital aphakia is a type of physical disorder and lens disease, which is based on some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It has the exact synonyms APHAKIA, CONGENITAL PRIMARY, and Congenital absence of lens.
Functional diarrhea is a type of colonic disease and is characterized by at least having the symptom of diarrhea. It is also exactly synonymous with functional diarrhoea.
Megacolon is a type of colonic disease and is defined as a colonic disease characterized by an abnormal dilation of the colon. It is also exactly synonymous with the term "Dilatation of the colon."

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:anal_spasm rdfs:subClassOf :anus_disease .
text: anal spasm is a type of anus disease.

Gnathomiasis, also known exactly as Gnathostomiasis or Infectious Disease by Gnathostoma, is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease. This disease has a material basis at least in part in Gnathostoma and presents symptoms including cough. It is defined as a parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that results from parasitic infection due to migrating immature worms of Gnathostoma spinigerum or Gnathostoma hispidum. The infection occurs by consuming undercooked fish or poultry that contains third-stage larvae or by drinking water with infective second-stage larvae in Cyclops. The migration of these larvae in the subcutaneous tissues leads to intermittent, migratory, painful, pruritic swellings known as cutaneous larva migrans. If the migration extends to other tissues, it results in visceral larva migrans, which can cause cough, hematuria, and ocular involvement. The most severe manifestations include eosinophilic meningitis with myeloencephalitis.

Spinal meningioma is defined as something that intersects with both a meningioma and a disease, specifically one that is located in the spinal cord. It is categorized as a type of meningioma as well as a type of spinal canal and spinal cord meningioma. Additionally, spinal meningioma is exactly synonymous with Spinal Cord meningioma.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:corneal_neovascularization rdfs:subClassOf :keratitis .
text: corneal neovascularization is a type of keratitis.
Cryptorchidism is a type of disorder of sexual development and has several exact synonyms including Cryptorchism, Undescended testicle, Undescended testis, and undescended testicles.

Expressive language disorder is a type of language disorder that is defined as a language disorder involving difficulties with verbal and written expression. It is characterized by an ability to use expressive spoken language that is markedly below the appropriate level for the mental age, yet with a language comprehension that is within normal limits. Expressive language disorder is also exactly synonymous with Developmental expressive language disorder.

An epidural abscess is the same as a disease that intersects with at least one disease located in the epidural space. It is a type of central nervous system disease. An epidural abscess is defined as a central nervous system disease characterized by a collection of pus (infected material) between the outer covering of the brain and spinal cord and the bones of the skull or spine, caused by an infection in the area between the bones of the skull or spine and the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord (meninges). Additionally, an epidural abscess has the exact synonym "abscess epidural."

Subdural empyema is a type of central nervous system disease and is defined as a central nervous system disease characterized by the collection or gathering of pus within the subdural space. It is also exactly synonymous with Subdural abscess.
Cerebral arteritis is a type of cerebrovascular disease and it is also a type of condition that, at a minimum, is a disease located in the cerebrum.

Adult Respiratory Distress Syndrome (ARDS) is a type of respiratory failure that is also recognized by several exact synonyms, including ARDS, Non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema, Shock lung, acute respiratory distress syndrome, and adult RDS. It is characterized by its onset during adulthood and can be associated with symptoms of shock. ARDS results from diffuse injury to the endothelium of the lung due to various causes such as sepsis, chest trauma, massive blood transfusion, aspiration of the gastric contents, or pneumonia. This condition is characterized by pulmonary edema with an abnormally high amount of protein in the edematous fluid, leading to difficult rapid breathing and hypoxemia.

Pulmonary edema is a type of respiratory failure and is defined as a respiratory failure characterized by the accumulation of fluid in the lung tissues. This condition causes a disturbance of gas exchange that may lead to respiratory failure.

Heart disease is equivalent to an entity that intersects with something that is a disease and has a location in the heart. Furthermore, heart disease is classified as a type of cardiovascular system disease. It is defined as a cardiovascular system disease that involves the heart.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:spinal_canal_and_spinal_cord_meningioma rdfs:subClassOf :spinal_cancer .
text: spinal canal and spinal cord meningioma is a type of spinal cancer.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:pyelonephritis rdfs:subClassOf :pyelitis .
text: pyelonephritis is a type of pyelitis.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:xanthogranulomatous_pyelonephritis rdfs:subClassOf :chronic_pyelonephritis .
text: xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis is a type of chronic pyelonephritis.

Diphtheria is a primary bacterial infectious disease, also known precisely as a Corynebacterium infection. It has a material basis in Corynebacterium diphtheriae, an aerobic Gram-positive bacterium. The disease is transmitted by contact transmission and droplet spread transmission. It is characterized by symptoms such as sore throat, low fever, and an adherent membrane on the tonsils, pharynx, and/or nasal cavity, with a milder form affecting the skin. The diphtheria toxin can spread through the bloodstream, leading to potentially life-threatening complications that impact the heart and kidneys.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:choroiditis rdfs:subClassOf :choroid_disease .
text: choroiditis is a type of choroid disease.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:alternating_exotropia rdfs:subClassOf :exotropia .
text: alternating exotropia is a type of exotropia.

Fallopian tube endometriosis is a condition that is the same as the intersection of endometriosis and a disease that has its location in the fallopian tube. It is a type of both fallopian tube disease and endometriosis. Fallopian tube endometriosis is defined as a female reproductive system disease characterized by the growth of endometrial tissue located in the fallopian tube. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "Endometriosis of the fallopian tube."
Endosalpingiosis is a type of endometriosis and is defined as a disease of the female reproductive system characterized by the growth of fallopian tube-like epithelium outside the fallopian tube.

Endometriosis of the intestine is defined as a condition where the intersection of endometriosis and a disease, which has its location in the intestine, is observed. It is a specific type of endometriosis as well as a type of intestinal disease. Moreover, endometriosis of the intestine is characterized as a female reproductive system disease marked by the growth of endometrial tissue located in the intestine.

Endometriosis of the pelvic peritoneum is a type of endometriosis, defined as a female reproductive system disease characterized by the growth of endometrial tissue that is located in the pelvic peritoneum.
Exotropia is a type of strabismus, which has exact synonyms: Divergent Strabismus and Divergent concomitant strabismus.
Endometriosis in the scar of the skin is a type of endometriosis, defined as a female reproductive system disease characterized by the growth of endometrial tissue located in the scar of the skin.

Endometriosis of the rectovaginal septum and vagina is a type of endometriosis defined as a female reproductive system disease. It is characterized by the growth of endometrial tissue located in the rectovaginal septum and vagina.

Endometriosis of the ovary is defined as a female reproductive system disease characterized by the growth of endometrial tissue located in the ovary, which is the same as something that intersects the categories of endometriosis and diseases with a location in the ovary. It is considered a type of ovarian disease as well as a type of endometriosis. Furthermore, endometriosis of the ovary has the exact synonym "ovarian endometriosis."

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:sciatic_neuropathy rdfs:subClassOf :lesion_of_sciatic_nerve .
text: sciatic neuropathy is a type of lesion of sciatic nerve.

Allergic cutaneous vasculitis is a type of allergic disease, hypersensitivity vasculitis, and something that at least has symptom some allergic reaction. It is defined as a hypersensitivity vasculitis that results in inflammation of small blood vessels, characterized clinically by palpable purpura, which is a slightly elevated purpuric rash over one or more areas of the skin. Additionally, allergic cutaneous vasculitis has exact synonyms: Allergic Cutaneous Angiitis and Autoimmune Hypersensitivity angiitis.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:perinatal_jaundice_due_to_hepatocellular_damage rdfs:subClassOf :neonatal_jaundice .
text: perinatal jaundice due to hepatocellular damage is a type of neonatal jaundice.

Brain compression is a type of brain disease and also falls under the category of conditions that have symptoms including at least some abscesses. It is defined as a brain disease characterized by pressure on the intracranial tissues caused by an effusion of blood or cerebrospinal fluid, an abscess, a neoplasm, a depressed fracture of the skull, or edema of the brain.

Pseudotumor cerebri, which is also exactly known as benign intracranial hypertension and idiopathic intracranial hypertension, is a type of intracranial hypertension. It is a condition that mimics a tumor, affecting the brain, which is its location.

Autonomic nervous system disease, which is also exactly known as autonomic nervous system disorder, is identified as a type of peripheral nervous system disease. This disease intersects with conditions that are diseases and also specifically have a location within the autonomic nervous system. Furthermore, it is defined as a peripheral nervous system disease that is located in the autonomic nervous system.

Subglottis cancer is equivalent to any condition that is both a cancer and a disease located in the subglottis. It is a specific type of larynx cancer and is exactly synonymous with Ca larynx - subglottis, malignant subglottic tumor, and malignant tumor of the subglottis.
Osteoporosis is a type of bone resorption disease characterized by a decreased density of normally mineralized bone. This results in the thinning of bone tissue and decreased mechanical strength.

Polydactyly is a type of physical disorder and a type of condition that at least has some abnormal digit morphology as its phenotype. It is defined as a physical disorder characterized by the presence of more than five fingers per hand or five toes per foot. Polydactyly is exactly synonymous with postaxial polydactyly and is also relatedly synonymous with a supernumerary digit.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:constrictive_pericarditis rdfs:subClassOf :pericarditis .
text: constrictive pericarditis is a type of pericarditis.
Hemopericardium is a type of pericardial effusion and is defined as a pericardial effusion that results from blood in the pericardial sac. It is exactly synonymous with Haemopericardium.

Horner's syndrome is a type of autonomic neuropathy and is defined as an autonomic neuropathy characterized by the classic triad of unilateral ptosis, unilateral miosis with anisocoria, and ipsilateral facial anhidrosis, resulting from unilateral paralysis of the cervical sympathetics. It has exact synonyms including Bernard Horner syndrome, Horner syndrome, and cervical sympathetic paralysis.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:idiopathic_peripheral_autonomic_neuropathy rdfs:subClassOf :autonomic_nervous_system_disease .
text: idiopathic peripheral autonomic neuropathy is a type of autonomic nervous system disease.

Acquired night blindness is a type of nutritional deficiency disease, defined as a nutritional deficiency disease characterized by vitamin A deficiency, which causes poor adaptation of the eyes to low levels of light. This condition has its material basis in the lack of vitamin A, such that rhodopsin, a light-sensitive retinal pigment, cannot be regenerated.

Cardiac tamponade is a type of pericardial effusion and is defined as a pericardial effusion in which fluid accumulates in the pericardium (the sac in which the heart is enclosed), and the pericardial spaces fill up faster than the pericardial sac can stretch. It has exact synonyms, including Rose's tamponade and pericardial tamponade.

text: Mitral valve insufficiency is a type of mitral valve disease and has exact synonyms including Congenital insufficiency of mitral valve, Mitral valve incompetence, congenital mitral insufficiency, congenital mitral regurgitation, and mitral regurgitation.

text: autonomic neuropathy is a type of autonomic nervous system disease.

Suppurative otitis media is a type of otitis media and is defined as a condition involving inflammation of the middle ear with infected effusion containing pus. It is also exactly synonymous with Otitis media with effusion - purulent and Purulent otitis media.
